<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="27" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="27">
<pageBreakToken pageId="16" pageNumber="27" start="start">Notes</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="27">
We examined two possible syntype females of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena croatica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="croatica">Andrena croatica</taxonomicName>
, which perfectly agree with the original description. No specimen was available for genetic study. These two females are markedly divergent from 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bicolor" pageId="16" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="bicolor">A. bicolor</taxonomicName>
, and thus 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. croatica" pageId="16" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="croatica">A. croatica</taxonomicName>
, which is currently considered as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bicolor" pageId="16" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="bicolor">A. bicolor</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gusenleitner, F" journalOrPublisher="Entomofauna, Supplement 10" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" title="Weltweite Checkliste der Bienengattung Andrena mit Bemerkungen und Erga ̈ nzungen zu pala ̈ arktischen Arten (Hymenoptera, Apidae, Andreninae, Andrena)." year="2002">Gusenleitner and Schwarz 2002</bibRefCitation>
), probably represents a valid species (stat. rev.). Striking divergent features in the female sex include the white scopa, the fine, regular punctation of the terga (Suppl. material 3: Fig. S9), the mesonotal vestiture comprising intermixed grey-brown hairs and numerous, comparatively long, dark hairs, and the numerous dark hairs on the propodeum. This species also has long mouthparts approaching the condition observed in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. allosa" pageId="16" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="allosa">A. allosa</taxonomicName>
(Suppl. material 3: Fig. S8). The male is unknown to us.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
